<br>
Monks defensive abilities were based on them being able to avoid more blows than other melee classes, but mitigate less. The increased avoidance was implemented via code, but the lower mitigation was implemented by restricting the AC on the gear normal monks were planned to use.<br>
<br>
There exists however several high AC all/all, or all melee items. Those were few at the start, but they were highly sought after among monks (Azure sleeves anyone?). Since the Velious and higher expansions, the number of monk usable high ac items has increased alot.<br>
<br>
Technically, Verant should not have included monks as a class on all/all or all melee items and given monks a similar quest result or drop with lower AC but otherwise equivalent. In the same way, but to a lesser extent, the chain classes should have been given an equivalent with less AC than the plate classes get.<br>
<br>
Instead of removing monks from the usable classes on existing high ac gear, and replacing now unusable gear for all monks with some lower ac equivalents, Verant has chosen to use a coding difference to make the monk get less benefits from wearing these high AC items than plate classes. This allows them to still keep the gear monk wearable, and not change the effect of it for people of other classes that might be wearing it.<br>
<br>
What effect that coding difference will have on monks not wearing high AC items remains to be seen.<br>
<br>
As a bonus for Verant, this helps lower the impact of some silly designers putting in high AC monk only items, which was a really bad decision. Those items could have been fixed by changing the AC on the item, but that won't be needed now, since there is a more general fix done already.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Was this a needed change, at this stage of the game?<br>
<br>
I don't know. The other three changes implemented at the same time were all changes which enabled them to put content in PoP that would have been broken had those features remained unchanged. <br>
<br>
 - They beta tested a short duration fight, and found out it was trivial with manaburn.<br>
 - They beta tested a longer duration fight where mana conservation was an issue, and found it was trivial with mod rods.<br>
 - They beta tested the possibilities with increased warrior HP, and found it to give too much increase to the value of CH.<br>
<br>
One guess could be that they were planning to continue the trend with all/all items, and realized during beta testing that monks wearing those new PoP items could much easier than before reach the point of diminishing returns for AC versus many mobs (where that point is depends on the mobs ATK, the guy who tested the Krup knight above would to me seem like an indication that krup knight vs monk has a cap in the neighborhood of 1050, or possibly lower). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ushamanixx.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shamanixx</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Disciple</span><br>  Posts: 351<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/13/02 8:04:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=80>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: you're kidding</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> First off Monks have the best melee damage from the front, period. This isn't even disputable. Rogues have the best melee from behind.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
